Column Comment.0: ANALYSIS IDENTIFIER: Unique identifier for a sample analysis. Various types ofanalysis may be conducted on a sample. Samples may be derived from lithologiccuttings, fluid collection etc.
Column Comment.1: ANALYSIS SOURCE: The source that the analysis came from, this could be a labtechnician, a lab, a company, a government agency, etc.
Column Comment.2: OIL ANALYSIS OBSSERVATION NUMBER: Unique identifier for this observation ofthe oil analysis done during this sample analysis. In many cases, only one record willexist.
Column Comment.3: ABSOLUTE GRAVITY: Use this column to keep track of the absolute gravitymeasured in vacuum.
Column Comment.5: ACTIVE INDICATOR: A Y or N flag indicating whether this row of data is currentlyeither active/valid (Y) or inactive/invalid (N).
Column Comment.6: ASPHALTENE CONTENT: The value of asphaltene in the crude oil mixture. Pendingon the original unit of measure this value could be volume, weight, percentage,quantity, etc.
Column Comment.8: ASPHALTENE CONTENT PREFERRED INDICATOR: A Y/N flag indicating whetheror not asphaltene content is preferred in the oil mixture. The asphaltene could createproblems even in small quantities if they are in light oils.
Column Comment.9: ASPHALTENE CONTENT PROBLEM INDICATOR: A Y/N flag indicating whether ornot there is a problem in the production, transportation or processing of the oil due tothe asphaltene content.
Column Comment.10: ASPHALTENE CONTENT STEP SEQUENCE NUMBER: A unique step sequencenumber for the step in the analysis of the asphaltene content in the crude oil.
Column Comment.12: ORIGINAL UNIT OF MEASURE: may not be required where the Watsoncharacterization factor is used.
Column Comment.13: CLOUD POINT PREFERRED INDICATOR: A Y/N flag indicating whether or not thedetermination of the cloud point is preferred.
Column Comment.14: CLOUD POINT PROBLEM INDICATOR: A Y/N flag indicating whether or not there isa problem in the determination of the cloud point.
Column Comment.15: CLOUD POINT STEP SEQUENCE NUMBER: A unique step sequence number forthe analysis leading to the determination of the cloud point.
Column Comment.16: CLOUD POINT TEMPERATURE: The temperature at which the first appearance ofmolecular agglomerates are formed.
Column Comment.18: DEW POINT PREFERRED INDICATOR: A Y/N flag indicating whether or not thedetermination of the dew point is preferred.
Column Comment.19: DEW POINT PROBLEM INDICATOR: A Y/N flag indicating whether or not there is aproblem in the determination of the dew point.
Column Comment.20: DEW POINT STEP SEQUENCE NUMBER: A unique step sequence number for theanalysis leading to the determination of the dew point.
Column Comment.21: DEW POINT TEMPERATURE: The temperature at which the first appearance of gascondensing to liquid.
Column Comment.23: DISTILLATION_BASE_TYPE: The base used for distillation
Column Comment.24: DISTILLATION PREFERRED INDICATOR: A Y/N flag indicating whether or not thedistillation of the oil is preferred.
Column Comment.25: DISTILLATION PROBLEM INDICATOR: A Y/N flag indicating whether or not there isa problem in the distillation of the oil.
Column Comment.26: DISTILLATION STEP SEQUENCE NUMBER: A unique step sequence number forthe distillation of the oil.
Column Comment.27: EFFECTIVE DATE: The date that the data in this row first came into effect.
Column Comment.28: EXPIRY DATE: The date that the data in this row was no longer active or in effect.
Column Comment.29: FLASH POINT PREFERRED INDICATOR: A Y/N flag indicating whether or not thedetermination of the flash point is preferred.
Column Comment.30: FLASH POINT PROBLEM INDICATOR: A Y/N flag indicating whether or not there isa problem in the determination of the flash point.
Column Comment.31: FLASH POINT STEP SEQUENCE NUMBER: A unique step sequence number forthe analysis leading to the determination of the flash point.
Column Comment.32: FLASH POINT TEMPERATURE: The temperature at which the oil will ignite but notcontinue to combust.
Column Comment.34: GAS OIL RATIO: Value for the volume of gas produced with the oil in the sample(GOR).
Column Comment.35: GAS OIL RATIO OUOM: Gas oil ratio original unit of measure.
Column Comment.36: MEASURED PRESSURE: Value for the amount of pressure recorded during the oildensity measurement.
Column Comment.37: MEASURED PRESSURE OUOM: Pressure amount original unit of measure.
Column Comment.38: MEASURED VOLUME: Volume of the oil fluid measured, usually for PVT analysis.
Column Comment.39: ORIGINAL UNIT OF MEASURE for this row of data
Column Comment.40: METHOD TYPE: The type of step that is applied during this method, such asgrinding, polishing, pyrolysis, slicing, spectroscopy, microscope analysis, countingetc.
Column Comment.41: OIL ANALYSIS TEMPERATURE: Value for the temperature of the oil when thedensity or specific gravity was measured.
Column Comment.42: OIL ANALYSIS TEMPERATURE OUOM: Temperature original unit of measure.
Column Comment.43: OIL COLOR: The color of the oil as it is being analyzed. For example, black, brown,light color, etc. This can have implications as to the type of the oil.
Column Comment.44: OIL COLOR PREFERRED INDICATOR: A Y/N flag indicating whether or not thedetermination of the oil color is preferred.
Column Comment.45: OIL COLOR PROBLEM INDICATOR:A Y/N flag indicating whether or not there is aproblem in the determination of the color of the oil.
Column Comment.46: OIL COLOR STEP SEQUENCE NUMBER: A unique step sequence number for theanalysis leading to the determination of the color of the oil.
Column Comment.47: OIL DENSITY: Value for the density or specific gravity of the oil sample, at aspecified temperature and pressure.
Column Comment.48: OIL DENSITY OUOM: Oil density original unit of measure.
Column Comment.49: OIL DENSITY PREFERRED INDICATOR: A Y/N flag indicating whether or not thedetermination of the oil density is preferred.
Column Comment.50: OIL DENSITY PROBLEM INDICATOR:A Y/N flag indicating whether or not there is aproblem in the determination of the density of the oil.
Column Comment.51: OIL DENSITY STEP SEQUENCE NUMBER: A unique step sequence number for theanalysis leading to the determination of the density of the oil.
Column Comment.52: OIL GRAVITY: API oil gravity. It is computed by dividing the specific gravity of a fluidat 60 F into 141.5 and subtracting 131.5.
Column Comment.54: OIL GRAVITY PREFERRED INDICATOR: A Y/N flag indicating whether or not thedetermination of the oil gravity is preferred.
Column Comment.55: OIL GRAVITY STEP SEQUENCE NUMBER: A unique step sequence number for theanalysis leading to the determination of the gravity of the oil.
Column Comment.56: OIL GRAVITY TEMPERATURE: The temperature at which the oil gravity wasdetermined.
Column Comment.58: OIL GRAVITY TEMPERATURE PREFERRED INDICATOR: A Y/N flag indicatingwhether or not the determination of the oil gravity temperature is preferred.
Column Comment.59: OILGRAVITY PROBLEM INDICATOR:A Y/N flag indicating whether or not there is aproblem in the determination of the gravity temperature of the oil.
Column Comment.60: OIL GRAVITY STEP SEQUENCE NUMBER: A unique step sequence number for theanalysis leading to the determination of the gravity temperature of the oil.
Column Comment.61: OIL TYPE: The type of oil being analyzed. For example, asphalt, crude, paraffin.
Column Comment.62: ROW_MANAGEMENT_GUID: This value may be used to provide a global uniqueidentifier for this row of data. Use of this column is not mandatory, but if used,optional PPDM NOT NULL and UNIQUE INDEX constraints provided in the datamodel DDL should be created.
Column Comment.63: RELATIVE DENISTY: Use this column to record the relative density of the oilcompared to the density in the column RELATIVE_STANDARD_DENSITY.
Column Comment.65: RELATIVE STANDARD DENSITY: The density of a standard substance underspecified conditions, this is used for comparison with RELATIVE_DENSITY.
Column Comment.67: REMARK: Narrative remarks about this row of data.
Column Comment.68: RESERVOIR PRESSURE: The reservoir pressure at the time the oil sample wasremoved for analysis.
Column Comment.70: RESERVOIR TEMPERATURE: The reservoir temperature at the time the oil samplewas removed for analysis.
Column Comment.72: SEDIMENT CONTENT: The value of sediment in the crude oil mixture. Pending onthe original unit of measure this value could be volume, weight, percentage, quantity,etc.
Column Comment.74: SEDIMENT CONTENT PREFERRED INDICATOR: A Y/N flag indicating whether ornot sediment content is preferred in the oil mixture.
Column Comment.75: SEDIMENT CONTENT PROBLEM INDICATOR: A Y/N flag indicating whether or notthere is a problem in the production, transportation or processing of the oil due to thesediment content.
Column Comment.76: SEDIMENT CONTENT STEP SEQUENCE NUMBER: A unique step sequencenumber for the step in the analysis of the sediment content in the crude oil.
Column Comment.77: SHRINKAGE FACTOR: The shrinkage factor is a measure of the volume loss due togas exsolution undergone by an oil which is brought from reservoir to stock tankconditions.
Column Comment.78: SHRINK FACTOR PREFERRED IND: A Y/N flag indicating whether or not theshrinkage factor is preferred.
Column Comment.79: SHRINK FACTOR PROBLEM IND: A Y/N flag indicating whether or not there isproblem with the shrinkage factor. If a yes flag is indicated, additional informationregarding the problem should be noted in the table ANL_PROBLEM.
Column Comment.80: SHRINK FACTOR STEP SEQUENCE NUMBER: A unique step sequence numberfor the shrinkage factor measurement.
Column Comment.81: SOURCE: The individual, company, state, or government agency designated as thesource of information for this row.
Column Comment.82: SULPHUR CONTENT: Value for the relative concentration of sulfur in the oil sample.(Measured in percent of weight.)
Column Comment.83: VAPOUR PRESSURE: Use this column to record the vapor pressure of the oil atequilibrium.
Column Comment.85: VAPOUR PRESSURE TEMPERATURE: Use this column to record the temperatureat which the vapor pressure of the oil was recorded.
Column Comment.87: WATER CONTENT: The value of water in the crude oil mixture. Pending on theoriginal unit of measure this value could be volume, weight, percentage, quantity, etc.
Column Comment.89: WAX CONTENT: The value of wax in the crude oil mixture. Pending on the originalunit of measure this value could be volume, weight, percentage, quantity, etc.
Column Comment.91: WAX PREFERRED INDICATOR: A Y/N flag indicating whether or not thedetermination of the wax content is preferred.
Column Comment.92: WAX PROBLEM INDICATOR:A Y/N flag indicating whether or not there is a problemin the determination of the wax content of the oil.
Column Comment.93: WAX STEP SEQUENCE NUMBER: A unique step sequence number for the analysisleading to the determination of the wax content of the oil.
Column Comment.94: ROW CHANGED BY: Application login id of the user who last changed the row.
Column Comment.95: ROW CHANGED DATE: System date of the last time the row was changed.
Column Comment.96: ROW CREATED BY: System user who created this row of data.
Column Comment.97: ROW CREATED DATE: Date that the row was created on.
Column Comment.98: ROW_EFFECTIVE_DATE: A system assigned date that specified when a row of datais effective from a systems perspective. This may be the date that a row of data wasmade available to end users, for example.
Column Comment.99: ROW_EXPIRY_DATE: A system assigned date that specified when a row of data isno longer effective from a systems perspective. This may be the date that a row ofdata was no longer available to end users, for example.
Column Comment.100: PPDM ROW QUALITY: A set of values indicating the quality of data in this row,usually with reference to the method or procedures used to load the data, althoughother types of quality reference are permitted.
